<!--
  AZUS README Template
  ====================
  Copy this file to Resources/README_template.html and customize for your project.

  This HTML file is used in two ways:
    1. Its content becomes the Zenodo record "description" field.
    2. It is saved as README.html alongside each dataset.

  Available template variables (Python string.Template $variable syntax):
    $esid              - Dataset identifier (e.g., "005")
    $date              - Formatted eclipse/event date (e.g., "April 08, 2024")
    $year              - Four-digit year (e.g., "2024")
    $eclipse_label     - Label from the eclipse_label() method (e.g., "Total Solar Eclipse")
    $latitude          - Site latitude in decimal degrees
    $longitude         - Site longitude in decimal degrees
    $coverage          - Eclipse coverage percentage
    $time_date_mode    - WAV file timestamp mode (e.g., "AudioMoth Time Chime")
    $first_contact     - Eclipse start time UTC
    $second_contact    - Totality start time UTC (may be "N/A")
    $maximum_time      - Eclipse maximum time UTC
    $third_contact     - Totality end time UTC (may be "N/A")
    $fourth_contact    - Eclipse end time UTC (may be "N/A")
    $start_time_notes  - Data collector start time notes

  You may add, remove, or rename variables to match your CSV column data.
  Variables that are not found in the collector data will be left as-is.
-->

